[BID 2D] Your partner has 12 to 14 balanced with no spade support, so rebids 1NT — a minimum balanced rebid that denies three spades for the moment, but the picture isn't final yet. ⟦You want to be sure about the spade fit, so bid 2\D — this is New Minor Forcing, an artificial, forcing call that has nothing to do with diamonds. It simply ask opener "do you hold three spades?"⟧
[BID Pass] Answering the ask, your partner shows three-card support by bidding 2\S — the cheapest way to confirm the major fit on a minimum. The new-minor inquiry has done its job. ⟦You pass; 2\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]The three-card support opener showed, opposite South's five spades, makes the eight-card fit, and with only modest combined values the partnership rests in 2\S rather than reaching for game. The lesson: when opener rebids 1NT over your major, a new-minor bid asks for hidden three-card support, and opener shows it cheaply with a minimum.}
